no-tiny-wrapper-function

Warns on tiny functions and methods that are three or fewer executable lines
and contain another function call.

Source: custom rule for lintcn
Severity: warn (does not block CI)

The goal is to stop agents from creating tiny wrapper abstractions when they
should inline the call directly at the usage site instead.

The Problem

These helpers often do not add meaningful behavior. They just rename a call and
make the codebase more indirect:

  export function createTestStore(): ConversationStore {
    return new ConversationStore(createMemoryRedis())
  }

  const save = (file: string) => write(file)

  class Repo {
    persist(value: string) {
      return write(value)
    }
  }

What Gets Flagged

- Functions with `<= 3` non-empty executable lines
- Methods with `<= 3` non-empty executable lines
- Bodies that contain a function call

This includes short wrappers such as:

  function persist(value: string) {
    const normalized = normalize(value)
    write(normalized)
    return normalized
  }

What Is Allowed

Short functions and methods are allowed when they only contain expressions and
do not call other functions:

  function sum(a: number, b: number) {
    return a + b
  }

  const getName = (user: { name: string }) => user.name

  class Counter {
    next() {
      return this.value + 1
    }
  }

Example Warning Messages

Function example:

  This function is only 1 line of code and contains a function call. Inline the
  call directly instead of creating a wrapper function.

Method example:

  This method is only 1 line of code and contains a function call. Inline the
  call directly instead of creating a wrapper function.
